english:
  title: Record of the Reconstruction of Yongam Temple on Yeongbong Mountain
  author: Park Jeonji
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Yongam Temple, where the Fearless National Preceptor descended to establish his seat, lies in the heart of Yeongbong Mountain, in the eastern corner of Banseong county, a prefecture of Jinyang. In ancient times, the Founding Patriarch Doseon, heeding a secret instruction from the Divine Mother and Celestial King, guardian deity of Jirisan, established three hermitages, for it was foretold that should three sacred caves be founded, the Three Hans would unite into one kingdom and warfare would naturally cease. Thus were founded the three hermitages—now known as Seonam, Unnam, and this very temple. And so this temple's great benefit to the nation is a truth known to all, past and present.

    Yet as the centuries grew distant from its founding, and successive abbots came and went without continuity, the halls crumbled, the Buddha images faded, and the Buddhist canon rotted away, until all seemed destined to vanish into dust. Our National Preceptor, in his youthful years, achieved the highest rank in the monastic examination, yet he renounced the snares of name and profit, returning to the mountains to dwell in hermitages for many years. When the king heard of his conduct, in the sixth year of Daedeok, the year of Imjin, summer, he sent an imperial messenger to receive him from the White Cloud Hermitage on Woleul Mountain and appointed him abbot of the Myoryeon Temple, a vowed sanctuary. In the tenth year, the year of Byungoh, winter, the king granted him the dharma-name White Moon Langkong Jeokjo Muae Great Zen Master. The following year, the year of Jeongmi, summer, when Prince Shim and his father the king wished to perform the disciples' bow, they enfeoffed him as Royal Teacher and elevated his dharma-name to Buddha Pojao Jeounghye Myowon Jingam Great Zen Master.

    Thereupon the king desired to make a renowned temple his seat of descent. At that time, Geumjang Temple stood unmanned and in disrepair. The master deemed this providential and petitioned repeatedly until it was granted as his seat. He immediately renovated the main hall, adorning with gold-plated copper the images of the principal Buddha Maitreya and the two Bodhisattvas of his succession. Records were made by the Councilor-in-Chief and Grand Academician Yi San.

    In the first year of Jidae, the year of Mushin, autumn, on the day Prince Shim ascended the throne, he summoned the master to sit beside him on the dragon throne and granted him the title of Universal Master of the Combined Schools of Zen and Teaching, entrusting him with shared deliberative affairs. In the year of Giyou, winter, the king commanded him to move to Gukcheong Temple, placing five temples—Oda, Suam, Joyeon, Annak, and Maru—under its jurisdiction as branch temples. A supervisory office was established for their repair. The master donated his entire stipend to construct the main hall and fashion images of Shakyamuni Buddha and the two Bodhisattvas of his succession, all adorned with pure gold. Records were written by Grand Councilor and Minister Min Ji and publicly displayed. When the five branch temples proved to be against his wishes, they were all returned to their original status.

    By the second year, the year of Gyeongsul, the king again commanded him to move to Yeongwon Temple. Yet since this temple had been the seat of a National Preceptor of the previous age, he wished to decline, though his wishes could not be fulfilled. There too he renovated the main hall and various buildings. In the second year of Huangqing, the year of Gyechuk, summer, the sixth month, when the present king ascended, by late autumn, the eleventh month, following his father's command, the king appointed him again as National Preceptor, elevating his dharma-name to Great Tiantai School Master, Double Propagator of Right and Wise Understanding, Illuminator of the Perfected Teaching, the Fearless National Preceptor.

    In the spring of the year Gapin of Yanyou, the first month, the master entered the inner palace for an audience. The king said, "Apart from this temple, there is no fitting place. Why do you persist in declining?" The master replied, "I have sworn never to be an abbot. Now, unable to escape this role, if the name of temple suffices, it is enough. Why should I concern myself with decay or flourishing, ease or difficulty?" His words were most earnest. Fearing to violate his wishes, the king commanded his removal to this temple.

    In the second year, the year of Eulmyo, the royal order was issued to Inspector Han Junghui and Salt Official Yi Baekgyeong to commence the great reconstruction. In the third year, the year of Byungjin, autumn, Inspector Park Hyosu also received the king's command and undertook a massive campaign. In the fourth year, the year of Jeongsa, Inspector Jeong Angyo, and in the fifth year, the year of Mugo, Inspector Yi Hwang and Salt Official Bang Ujeong also received the king's command to oversee the work to completion.

    All told, more than eighty new structures were built and more than twenty old ones repaired. The roof tiles were laid in scales, the eaves flew like wings, the painted walls stood in neat rows both lengthwise and crosswise, while stone steps ascended like clouds above and below. Within the halls, paper was stretched and woven mats laid, all glazed with five-colored lacquer until no beauty was lacking. The great image of Shakyamuni Buddha in the main hall and the images of Avalokiteshvara and Zhixu Bodhisattvas in the subsidiary shrine were gilded with the master's own resources and donations from others, until gold gleamed upon the Buddha's form and the five colors shone upon the Bodhisattvas' faces.

    For the Buddhist canon, Former Salt Officials Yi and Bang separately received the king's order and produced more than thirty thousand snow-white pages and one hundred forty lacquered cases to assist. The master's disciples, Great Zen Masters Seunguk, Jungdeok, and Ilsaeng, traveled to the printing blocks at Ganghwa and brought newly printed and old volumes, making over six hundred cases in total. All were bound in yellow silk and enshrined in the new hall and new repository. Salt Official Bang again received the king's order and on the eighteenth day of the eleventh month of the fifth year, received the master as he entered the temple. For about seven days a grand dedication ceremony was held, the Buddhist canon recited by day and profound teachings expounded by night, prayers offered for the king's longevity and the people's blessing, and thus was the great work completed.

    Ah, how wondrous! This National Preceptor, having received the honor of three successive kings bowing as disciples, has become the teacher of the realm—reviving the Buddha's way and reinvigorating the teachings, performing vast Buddhist works for the benefit of all people. How can his virtue and accomplishment be fully reckoned? Moreover, this very place first encountered Patriarch Doseon and was founded four hundred years ago, when our Great Founder was born and unified the Three Kingdoms into one court. For long ages it lay in desolate silence, until now it meets again with a king devoted to the Buddha's teaching and a master of ancient vows, and is rebuilt four hundred years later to gather three into one through the dharma of universal redemption. How can this perfect correspondence across the centuries be but divine? Perhaps place itself has its appointed time and meeting. Such a worthy achievement deserves to be inscribed upon precious jade and transmitted forever. I, at the entreaty of the National Preceptor's disciples, have set down these records of dates and events.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The three hermitages (Seonam, Unnam, and Yongam temples) are traditionally attributed to the legendary founding patriarch Doseon and were believed to symbolize the unification of Korea's Three Kingdoms.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Fearless National Preceptor' (Muae Gukdong) was the highest rank of Buddhist prelate in medieval Korea, combining both spiritual authority and political influence.
  - key: ''
    value: The reconstruction involved coordination across five years (1351-1355 CE in the Goryeo calendar) under multiple royal officials and inspectors, indicating the considerable importance and resources devoted to this temple's revival.
